This law is constitutional because Congress has broad authority under the **Commerce Clause** (Article I, Section 8) to regulate interstate commerce, including the shipment of goods across state lines, especially when public health concerns are involved. The restriction on unprescribed sales does not violate free trade rights (B) or property rights (C), nor does it infringe on privacy (I) or freedom of choice (J) in a way that would render it unconstitutional. The law aligns with Congress’s power to address harmful substances (D) and public health (G/H), but **A** is the most precise and foundational justification.
